<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters may be able to find neither rhyme
nor reason in the workings of state government, but the governor
hopes to change that. Louisiana is looking for a poet laureate.
   ``We are looking for someone like a (Carl) Sandburg, a T.S.
Eliot or a Robert Frost,'' Ray Beasley of the Department of
Culture, Recreation and Tourism said Monday.
   The state Arts Council is looking for a poet to serve as the
state's chief balladeer, extolling the virtues of Louisiana and the
state's ``literary excellence and understanding of the literary
arts,'' Beasley said.
   The position was created in 1942, but Louisiana has not had a
poet laureate since Jean M. Boese of Alexandria left office along
with Gov. Edwin Edwards in 1988.
   Gov. Buddy Roemer will name the poet after receiving
recommendations from the arts panel.
</TEXT>
